The closest thing to zero

00:00:18.340 --> 00:00:21.540
it's called an infinitesimal. is it even a thing?

00:00:22.660 --> 00:00:27.380
Because there is something about that, that makes you feel a bit uncomfortable

00:00:27.400 --> 00:00:33.880
It's been an idea that's been controversial for a long time, I mean thousands of years.

00:00:33.880 --> 00:00:36.260
Some people like it. Some people hate it.

00:00:36.400 --> 00:00:39.020
So what an infinitesimal would be?

00:00:39.040 --> 00:00:42.980
A smallest number possible close to zero as possible

00:00:43.840 --> 00:00:46.640
so it would be something that's bigger than zero

00:00:47.440 --> 00:00:57.680
but is smaller than all other numbers let's say 'r' for real number. It is smaller than everything else. That is slightly uncomfortable because of this:

00:00:58.400 --> 00:01:00.120
if you have two numbers,

00:01:00.140 --> 00:01:02.180
if we have 'a' less that 'b'

00:01:02.180 --> 00:01:06.400
there is always a number that I can fit in between

00:01:06.400 --> 00:01:09.560
let's call it 'c', there is always something I can fit in between

00:01:09.560 --> 00:01:10.720
and I can prove that because

00:01:11.140 --> 00:01:14.900
'c' could be a+b divided by two

00:01:15.220 --> 00:01:16.400
and that's proven.

00:01:16.420 --> 00:01:18.480
There is always something that you can slip in

00:01:18.480 --> 00:01:21.480
between two numbers, no matter how close you think they are.

00:01:21.480 --> 00:01:23.480
- Can't we slip in something else?

00:01:23.480 --> 00:01:25.480
So the idea of

00:01:25.480 --> 00:01:27.480
having the next number

00:01:27.480 --> 00:01:29.480
to zero makes intuitive sense

00:01:31.080 --> 00:01:33.080
but mathematically

00:01:33.080 --> 00:01:35.080
it's alarm bells ring.

00:01:35.080 --> 00:01:37.080
So this has always been a problem.

